    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-10-01T07:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-10-01T07:30:00-05:00" n="827"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d827">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">689.90D/10–152: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in India</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BCB1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bowles</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d827fn1">This telegram was repeated for information to
                        Karachi, Kabul; and Moscow.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-10-01T18:00:00+05:30"
                            >October 1, 1952—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1398. In conversation with <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> officer yesterday
                    afternoon, Acting Foreign Secy <persName corresp="#p_NRK1">R. K.
                        Nehru</persName> stated <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> is deeply
                    concerned re recent <gloss target="#t_Sov1">Sov</gloss>
                    <hi rend="italic">démarche</hi> to Afghan Govt, asserting it <gloss
                        target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> policy to foster strong and indep Afghan in
                    basic interest of <gloss target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss> security, which no less
                    than that entertained by <gloss target="#t_Brit1">Brit</gloss> when they
                    controlled <gloss target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss>. <persName corresp="#p_NJ1"
                        >Nehru</persName> said <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss> policy of
                    blocking ingress to Afghan had compelled latter to enter into closer econ and
                    polit ties with USSR, a development inimical to the democracies and definitely
                    contrary to <gloss target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss>’s desires. He therefore
                    considered it in interests of <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss>, <gloss
                        target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss> and Western democracies to persuade <gloss
                        target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss> to grant unrestricted transit facilities into
                    Afghan. In this connection he observed <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss>
                    should be urged to observe terms of “Barcelonan Conv.”<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d827fn2">The Barcelona Convention of 1921 provided for the
                        internationalization of navigable waterways that separate or traverse
                        different states. (Whiteman, <hi rend="italic">Digest of International
                            Law</hi>, III, 879–880)</note> When <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss>
                    officer raised Pushtoonistan question and suggested <gloss target="#t_GOA1"
                        >GOA</gloss> should be urged to cease using this issue against <gloss
                        target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss>, <persName corresp="#p_NRK1">Nehru</persName>
                    defended Afghan position, asserting these tribes-people never tamed, not even by
                        <gloss target="#t_Brit1">Brit</gloss>, and what <gloss target="#t_GOA1"
                        >GOA</gloss> sought for tribespeople from <gloss target="#t_Pak1"
                        >Pak</gloss> was their cultural autonomy. <gloss target="#t_Pak1"
                        >Pak</gloss>, he said, on other hand, wanted <gloss target="#t_GOA1"
                        >GOA</gloss> to eat humble pie renouncing all interest in tribespeople,
                    something <gloss target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss> could hardly do. Altho <gloss
                        target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> officer pressed point repeatedly <persName
                        corresp="#p_NRK1">Nehru</persName> indicated <gloss target="#t_GOI1"
                        >GOI</gloss> supported <gloss target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss> position re
                    Pushtoonistan issue and unwilling suggest <gloss target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss>
                    drop propaganda and other activities.</p>
                <p>It seems to <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_Sov1">Sov</gloss> action offers good opportunity explore
                    possibility of bringing about better relations between Afghan and <gloss
                        target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss>. I am seeing <gloss target="#t_PriMin1"
                        >PriMin</gloss>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d827fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Jawaharlal Nehru</persName>.</note> later today
                    and hope to find opportunity discuss matter with him.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bowles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
